\begin_layout Section
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As firms are required to complete all industry tasks their production function naturally takes a Leontief form.
 We show that we can obtain a macro,
 industry-wide CES production function by aggregating individual firms' micro Leontief production functions if firms have heterogenous AI quality levels whose distribution follows a specific form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our model production occurs in two stages.
 In the first stage,
 uncertain about their AI productivity levels,
 firms commit to an automation strategy and job design by minimizing expected costs.
 In the second stage,
 productivity is realized,
 and firms either produce according to a Leontief production function within the chosen job design or exit the market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I show that a particular distribution of firm-level AI productivity heterogeneity enables this micro-to-macro aggregation,
 providing a theoretical foundation for CES production functions in economies adopting AI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Two-Stage Production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[PS:
 I jump to describing the model assuming the Steps–Tasks–Jobs–Industry hierarchy is discussed earlier and the reader knows the production structure.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A unit mass of firms operates in the industry,
 with each firm performing all $m$ steps $s_1,
 
\backslash
ldots,
 s_m$ to produce the industry good.
 Firms are randomly assigned an AI quality level (parameter $
\backslash
alpha$) that determines how efficiently they can deploy AI technology to execute tasks,
 but are otherwise identical.
 Before quality levels are realized,
 all firms share the same beliefs about their expected AI deployment effectiveness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Production occurs in two stages.
 In the first stage,
 firms solve a cost minimization problem by choosing job designs based on their expected AI quality levels.
 Since firms are identical ex ante,
 they hold identical expectations over AI quality levels and make identical automation and job-design choices.
 In the second stage,
 AI quality levels are realized and firms produce according to a Leontief production function determined by the automation strategy and job design to which they committed in the first stage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This two-stage process reflects realistic firm behavior:
 firms first decide how to structure their operations and post job vacancies.
 After making these structural decisions,
 they hire workers and acquire machines to begin production.
 Only after hiring do they discover the actual productivity of their labor and capital,
 forcing them to operate under their previously committed organizational structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While having each firm produce according to a Leontief function under a different realized AI quality level appears to create analytical complexity,
 we show that this heterogeneity can be structured to yield a tractable industry-level analysis.
 Our key insight is that with an appropriate distribution of AI quality across firms,
 individual Leontief production functions aggregate into an industry-level CES production function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We accomplish this aggregation in two stages:
\end_layout

