\begin_layout Subsection
Within-Firm Aggregation:
 Leontief to (Aggregate) Leontief
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with the within-firm aggregation.
 All variables discussed in this section have an implicit firm subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 which we drop for notational simplicity.
 But reader should have in mind that the analysis of the current subsection is for a single firm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose tasks 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are completed manually and tasks 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 are completed using AI.
 Given that the job design is fixed,
 we can treat hand-offs as standalone tasks with 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0$
\end_inset

 and time requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume all hand-offs are executed manually by the worker who completes the last task of the job.
 This allows us to change the order in which tasks are completed without loss.
 Specifically,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}=\{1,\cdots,k\}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of AI-executed and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}=\{k+1,\cdots,n,n+1,n+J-1\}$
\end_inset

 denote the set of human-executed tasks.
 The task-level production function of the firm can be written in the following Leontief form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\min\,\{\frac{l_{1}}{t_{1}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{1}}}\,,\,\cdots\,,\,\frac{l_{k}}{t_{k}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{k}}}\,,\,\frac{l_{k+1}}{t_{k+1}^{h}}\,,\,\cdots\,,\,\frac{l_{n}}{t_{n}^{h}}\,,\,\frac{l_{s^{1}}}{t_{1}^{s}}\,,\,\cdots\,,\,\frac{l_{s^{J-1}}}{t_{J-1}^{s}}\}.\label{eq:task_level_prod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here,
 the left hand side is the firm's output (i.e.,
 the industry good) normalized to 1,
 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of labor assigned to task 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 per unit of output,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{s^{j}}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of labor dedicated to do the hand-off between job 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j+1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 implicitly assumes the firm's automation strategy and job design is fixed.
 That is,
 it takes the allocation of tasks to AI or human execution (hence,
 the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

) as well as the job boundaries as given.
 Thus,
 the required amount of time to spend on each task is fixed for the firm and it treats all parameters in the denominator of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the Leontief nature of production,
 equilibrium allocation of inputs to tasks is fixed at
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\frac{l_{1}}{t_{1}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{1}}}=\cdots=\frac{l_{k}}{t_{k}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{k}}}=\frac{l_{k+1}}{t_{k+1}^{h}}=\cdots=\frac{l_{n}}{t_{n}^{h}}=\frac{l_{s^{1}}}{t_{1}^{s}}=\cdots=\frac{l_{s^{J-1}}}{t_{J-1}^{s}}.
\]

\end_inset

For each firm,
 the ratio of amount of labor assigned to any two input 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 above (regardless of mode of execution) is independent of units of output produced and wage rates,
 and depends only on the relative time requirements of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 which are fixed.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{l_{i}}{l_{j}}=const_{ij}.\label{eq:fixed_labor_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The fixed ratio of labor inputs implies that the rate of substitution between any pair of tasks is independent of amount dedicated to production of other tasks.
 That is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{∂}{∂l_{z}}\left(\frac{\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta l_{i}}}{\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta l_{j}}}\right)=0\qquad\qquad\forall z\neq i,j.\label{eq:task_subst_rate_indep}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A necessary and sufficient condition for aggregating a firm's production function from a Leontief with an input for each task to a Leontief with (firm-level) aggregate human labor and AI labor inputs is that the rate of substitution between any two tasks of the same aggregated type is independent of any task in the other aggregated type (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Leontief, 1947"
target "https://www.jstor.org/stable/1905335?seq=1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Fisher, 1965"
target "https://academic.oup.com/restud/article-abstract/32/4/263/1545778"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Felipe and Fisher, 2003"
target "https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/1467-999X.00166"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 In other words,
 the relative hired amount for any two human-executed tasks (respectively,
 AI-executed tasks) is only determined by tasks in the human-executed (respectively,
 AI-executed) group.
 The condition expressed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_subst_rate_indep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 satisfies this property.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The condition in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_subst_rate_indep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is in fact stricter than needed for obtaining the within-firm aggregation result.
 It not only satisfies our desired property but also provides a stronger requirement:
 that the rate of substitution between tasks within the same (firm-level) aggregate input type is also independent of other modules within that same aggregated input type.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus,
 we can represent the production function of the firm in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\min\,\{\frac{l_{M}}{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{i}}}\,,\,\frac{l_{H}}{\sum_{j=1}^{J-1}\,t_{j}^{s}+\sum_{i=k+1}^{n}\,t_{i}^{h}}\},\label{eq:task_level_agg_prod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{H}$
\end_inset

 are the firm-aggregate AI labor and firm-aggregate human labor employed per unit of the industry good produced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For ease of notation let us transform 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_agg_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 into a more readable format by defining a few new variables.
 Define firm-level aggregate human and AI time requirements as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{M}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m},\label{eq:def_t_AI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{H}=\sum_{j=1}^{J-1}\,t_{j}^{s}+\sum_{i=k+1}^{n}\,t_{i}^{h}\label{eq:def_t_H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 be the composite,
 firm-level AI quality:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\alpha}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{i}}}{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m}},\label{eq:alpha_bar}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{M}\,\bar{\alpha}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}\,t_{i}^{m}\,\alpha^{-d_{i}}.
\]

\end_inset

With these variables,
 we can rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:task_level_agg_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=\min\,\{\frac{l_{M}}{t_{M}\ \bar{\alpha}}\,,\,\frac{l_{H}}{t_{H}}\}.\label{eq:micro_agg_prod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This completes the within-firm aggregation step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Across Firm Aggregation:
 (Aggregate) Leontief to CES
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A substantial literature examines how micro-level production functions can be represented by a single macro-level production function.
 Each input in the macro production function is an aggregation of the corresponding inputs from the micro-level functions.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Sato (1975),
 Chapters 2 and 4,
 for conditions of existence,
 and Baqaee and Farhi (2019) for a recent overview.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The central idea is that with proper type of heterogeneity across firms,
 aggregated inputs will exhibit desirable forms.
 That is,
 to map specific micro-level production functions (e.g.,
 Leontief,
 Cobb-Douglas) onto specific macro-level functions (e.g.,
 Cobb-Douglas,
 CES),
 the distribution of firms' inputs must exhibit particular properties that support this aggregation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For instance,
 Houthakker studies the aggregation from micro-level Leontief to macro-level Cobb-Douglas functions,
 Levhari investigates aggregation from micro-level Leontief to macro-level CES functions,
 and Sato explores aggregation from micro-level CES to macro-level CES functions.
 See Baqaee and Farhi for a broader formulation of this aggregation issue.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section,
 we aim to represent micro-level Leontief production functions,
 whose inputs include firm-level aggregate human labor,
 AI management labor,
 and capital,
 with a macro-level CES production function whose inputs are aggregate human labor,
 AI management labor,
 and capital (following Levhari).
 In particular,
 suppose the macro-level production function takes the following form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X=\left(\theta_{M}\,M+\theta_{H}\,H^{\rho}+(1-\theta_{M}-\theta_{H})\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho}}.\label{eq:macro_agg_prod-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here,
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 represents the aggregate AI labor at the macro-level and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 represents the aggregate human labor while 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 on the left-hand-side is the aggregate output.
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{M}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{H}$
\end_inset

 are the expenditure shares of corresponding inputs.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As measure of firms is 1 capital also aggregates to 1.
 Hence,
 the third term in the macro production function appears as a constant.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To connect the macro-level CES production function with the micro-level Leontief functions,
 we must relate the aggregate parameters of individual firm variables (as specified in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:micro_agg_prod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

