\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium Allocations when Human and AI Labor are of the Same Kind
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{H}=\frac{H}{M}=\int_{\theta_{H}^{-\frac{1}{\rho}}}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt.\label{eq:macro_inputs_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The equilibrium amount of industry-level 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 will be determined based on supply of different kinds of inputs along with equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:macro_inputs_ratio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume other than required trainings (captured through 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 s) a worker can spend their time executing a manual task or managing an AI chain.
 In other words,
 assume human labor and AI labor are of the same kind.
 Suppose the homogenous labor has a total fixed supply of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 split between 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and the shared wage rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 (i.e.,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{H}=w_{M}=w(=v_{L}+\sum c_{i}?)$
\end_inset

).
 Labor market clearing implies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L=H+M.\label{eq:total_labor_supply}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting for 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:macro_inputs_ratio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:total_labor_supply"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 gives total labor allocated to AI across the industry
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M=\frac{L}{1+\int_{\theta_{H}^{-\frac{1}{\rho}}}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt}.\label{eq:AI_labor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly,
 the share of human labor in the industry will be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H=\frac{L\ \int_{\theta_{H}^{-\frac{1}{\rho}}}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt}{1+\int_{\theta_{H}^{-\frac{1}{\rho}}}^{\frac{1}{w}}\ t\ g(t)\ dt}.\label{eq:human_labor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The expression for industry-level AI employment has a nice comparative static result:
 AI employment goes up following an increase in AI quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 This is because,
 for a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}/t_{M}$
\end_inset

,
